>brown spotted cod</strong>, or <strong>bumblebee grouper</strong>, and as the <strong>Queensland grouper</strong> in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia\" title=\"Australia\">Australia</a>, is the largest <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Osteichthyes\" title=\"Osteichthyes\">bony fish</a> found in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coral_reef\" title=\"Coral reef\">coral reefs</a>, and the aquatic emblem of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queensland\" title=\"Queensland\">Queensland</a>. It is found from near the surface to depths of 100&nbsp;m (330&nbsp;ft) at reefs throughout the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indo-Pacific\" title=\"Indo-Pacific\">Indo-Pacific</a> region, with the exception of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Persian_Gulf\" title=\"Persian Gulf\">Persian Gulf</a>. It also enters <a class=\"mw-redirect\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estuaries\" title=\"Estuaries\">estuaries</a>,<sup><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giant_grouper#cite_note-fishbase-2\">[2]</a></sup> such as the lowermost part of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brisbane_River\" title=\"Brisbane River\">Brisbane River</a>. It reaches up to 2.7&nbsp;m (8.9&nbsp;ft) in length and 400&nbsp;kg (880&nbsp;lb) in weight;<sup><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giant_grouper#cite_note-fishbase-2\">[2]</a></sup> unconfirmed reports of it growing much bigger exist, up to 4.26&nbsp;m (14.0&nbsp;ft) and 598&nbsp;kg (1,318&nbsp;lb).<sup>[<em><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Citation needed\">citation needed</a></em>]</sup> Giant groupers feed on a variety of marine life, including small <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shark\" title=\"Shark\">sharks</a> and juvenile <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sea_turtle\" title=\"Sea turtle\">sea turtles</a>. Due to <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overfishing\" title=\"Overfishing\">overfishing</a>, this species has declined drastically in many regions, and as of the mid-1990s, it is considered <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vulnerable_species\" title=\"Vulnerable species\">Vulnerable</a> by the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Union_for_Conservation_of_Nature\" title=\"International Union for Conservation of Nature\">IUCN</a>.<sup><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giant_grouper#cite_note-IUCN-1\">[1]</a></sup></p>\r\n','','full_html'),('node','page',0,3,3,'und',0,'<p>d71 test site</p>\r\n','','filtered_html');
